    "id": "pickleball-for-beginners",
    "title": "Pickleball for Beginners: Rules, Equipment, and Where to Start in the PH",
    "date": "June 26, 2026",
    "category": "Guides",
    "image": "https://images.unsplash.com/photo-1779862753112-418ae8909c8c?w=800&q=75",
    "excerpt": "New to pickleball? Here's everything you need to know to start playing in the Philippines — from rules and scoring to equipment and finding courts.",
    "content": "<p><strong>New to pickleball? Here's everything you need to know to start playing in the Philippines — from rules and scoring to equipment and finding courts.</strong> Pickleball is one of the easiest sports to learn, and most beginners are rallying within 15 minutes of their first session. This guide covers the absolute essentials.</p><h3>The Absolute Basics</h3><p>Pickleball is played on a badminton-sized court (20x44 feet) with a low net (34 inches at center). Players use solid paddles to hit a perforated plastic ball over the net. The game can be played as singles or doubles, though doubles is by far the most common format in the Philippines.</p><h3>Scoring Made Simple</h3><p>Games are played to 11 points (win by 2). Only the serving team can score. In doubles, the score is called as three numbers: the serving team's score, the receiving team's score, and the server number (1 or 2). For example, \"4-2-1\" means the serving team has 4, the receiving team has 2, and it's the first server's turn.</p><h3>The Two-Bounce Rule</h3><p>This is the most important rule to remember: after the serve, the receiving team must let the ball bounce once before returning it. Then, the serving team must also let the return bounce once before playing it. After these two bounces, players can volley (hit the ball in the air) or play it off the bounce. This rule prevents serve-and-volley dominance and creates longer rallies.</p><h3>The Kitchen (Non-Volley Zone)</h3><p>The 7-foot area on each side of the net is called \"the kitchen.\" You cannot step into this zone to volley the ball. This rule prevents players from smashing at close range and rewards strategic placement over power.</p><h3>Gear to Get Started</h3><p>You need: a pickleball paddle (P1,000-P3,000 for entry-level), outdoor pickleballs (P300-P600 for a pack), court shoes with lateral support, and a water bottle. That's it. Most venues rent equipment for P50-P100 per session, so you can try before you buy.</p><h3>Where to Start in the PH</h3><p>SM malls with Active Hub pickleball courts are the easiest places to start — affordable rates, rental equipment, and friendly staff. Other beginner-friendly venues include BGC Pickleball Courts, Quezon City Memorial Circle, and Alabang Country Club. Join the Pickleball Philippines Facebook group and post your location — you'll have playing partners within hours.</p>",
    "author": "PickleSpotPH"
